		<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
		     SECTION — PREFACE & A NOTE ON THE TRANSLATION
		     ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
		<Section variant="soft">
			<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto" style="font-family: var(--font-sans); color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.8;">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-3" style="color: var(--color-gold);">The Heart Behind It</p>
				<h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light mb-8" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">Preface</h2>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">The destination was always the Father</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>Jesus said, “I am the way, the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me” (John 14:6). For generations the church heard the way to heaven. He said the way to the Father. The destination was never merely forgiveness, and never merely heaven. It was the Father Himself.</p>
					<p>From the first page to the last, Scripture tells one story: a perfect and loving Father pursuing and restoring His beloved sons and daughters through the blood of His Son and by the Holy Spirit. Father's Heart Bible™ exists for one reason: so you can hear that story in the Father's own voice, and come home.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">What this translation does, and does not do</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>Father's Heart Bible™ does not add to Scripture's meaning, nor take away from it. It is a faithful translation of the original Hebrew, Aramaic, and Greek that recovers an emphasis already present in the text: the revelation of God as Father.</p>
					<p>Consider the best-known verse in the Bible. “For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son” (John 3:16). The Greek word rendered “God” is theos, and here it plainly means the Father, the One who sends and gives the Son. Father's Heart Bible™ makes the obvious explicit: “For our Father so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son.” This is not addition. It is revealing what the text has been saying the whole time.</p>
					<p>You will find the same all through Scripture. When Adam and Eve hid in the garden, they hid not from a distant deity but from their Father (Genesis 3:8). When God covered their shame with His own hands, it was the Father who clothed them (Genesis 3:21). The words were always there. We are simply letting them be heard.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">What “God” and “the LORD” concealed</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>The original languages carry distinctions that centuries of English flattened. Hebrew speaks of God by many names: Elohim, El Shaddai, Adonai, the covenant name YHWH, and also, tenderly, as Ab, Father. The translation tradition gathered nearly all of these under “God” and “the LORD.” Something true was preserved, but something true was also lost: a near and personal Father came to sound like a remote and impersonal deity.</p>
					<p>Notice who, in Scripture, relates to God only as a distant deity and never as Father. The serpent in Eden, who recast a generous Father as a withholding rival: “Did God really say…?” (Genesis 3:1). The accuser and the arguing friends in Job, who debated a remote and transactional judge, until Job himself moved from hearing about God to seeing Him: “My ears had heard of you, but now my eyes have seen you” (Job 42:5). Pharaoh, who sneered, “Who is the LORD, that I should obey him?” (Exodus 5:2). Even the tempter in the wilderness aimed his attack straight at the bond of sonship: “If you are the Son of God…” (Matthew 4:3).</p>
					<p>The enemy's strategy has never changed since the garden: to make the Father seem distant, demanding, and disappointed. For too long, “God” and “the LORD” left that caricature unchallenged. Father's Heart Bible™ lets the Hebrew and Greek speak the distinction they always made, between a deity to be appeased and a Father to be received.</p>
					<p>The approach we follow is simple and transparent: every rendering follows the text's own witness, and the reasoning behind our choices is open to view.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">Our lens, and why it is honest</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>Every translation interprets; none is neutral. Ours carries a stated lens: we listen for the Father's voice and name Him where Scripture reveals Him as Father. We want to be honest that this is a lens, and honest about where it comes from.</p>
					<p>We read the whole of Scripture in the light of the whole of Scripture. Three realities now shape how we translate, beginning at the very first verse: first, the incarnation — the Son revealed the Father perfectly (“Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father,” John 14:9); second, Pentecost — the Spirit of sonship was poured out, crying from within His children, “Abba, Father” (Romans 8:15; Galatians 4:6); third, the sealed canon — with the last book written, the whole story finally came into view: one Father, one redemption, one family.</p>
					<p>These are not later ideas read backward into an unwilling text. The Father, the Son, and the Spirit were present and at work in Genesis 1:1. To read Genesis in the light of John is not anachronism; it is reading the first chapter by the same Author who wrote the last. The Father did not become Father at Bethlehem. He has always been Father.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">The Trinity, rightly seen</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>This recovery does not diminish the Trinity; it clarifies it. The one God exists eternally as Father, Son, and Holy Spirit, three persons in one essence, and Father's Heart Bible™ honors each. The Father initiates, sends, and gives. The Son reveals, redeems, and reconciles us to the Father. The Spirit applies, confirms, and pours the Father's love into our hearts.</p>
					<p>What this translation refuses is a caricature many have unknowingly carried: a gentle Jesus, a powerful Spirit, and behind them an old, distant, disappointed Father. That Father does not exist. The Father is exactly like Jesus, for Jesus is His perfect image.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">A word about the word “Father”</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>We know that for many, “father” is not a word of comfort. It can carry absence, disappointment, even deep wounds. If that is your story, this Bible is especially for you. The Father revealed in these pages is not a projection of broken human fatherhood. He is the original, the Father from whom every family in heaven and on earth takes its name (Ephesians 3:14–15). Every good thing an earthly father does is a faint echo of His heart; every failure is a departure from it. He is the Father you were made for — the One who will never leave you, and never let you go.</p>
				</div>

				<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">Come home</h3>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>From the garden, where the Father walked with His children in the cool of the day, to the final page, where He declares, “I will be their Father, and they will be my sons and daughters” (Revelation 21:7), Scripture tells one unbroken story: a perfect and loving Father pursuing and restoring His beloved through the blood of His Son and by the Holy Spirit.</p>
					<p>You are not an outsider. You are not an orphan. You are not a servant hoping for scraps at the table. You are the Father's beloved child — and He has been waiting for you the whole time.</p>
					<p><em>Welcome to Father's Heart Bible™. Come home.</em></p>
				</div>

				<h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light mt-16 mb-8" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); color: var(--color-ink);">A Note on the Translation</h2>
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<p>Father's Heart Bible™ is an interpretive translation. On the familiar spectrum from word-for-word to thought-for-thought, it renders the meaning of the original in clear, contemporary English, and at chosen places makes explicit the Father's identity, presence, and voice the text already carries. This emphasis on the Father is its distinctive purpose; it stands within historic, Trinitarian Christian belief and seeks to reveal what the text already contains. Some of its renderings are therefore theological as well as lexical. At Genesis 1:1, for instance, “God” (Elohim) is rendered “our Heavenly Father.”</p>
					<p>Where a word for God stands in a clearly relational or covenantal setting, it is rendered “our Father.” Elsewhere the customary rendering is kept, and Adonai and Kurios are always rendered “Lord.” Some choices are marked with a brief note (including where the original carries no divine name), so the reader sees both what the text says and what has been drawn from it. These notes serve the reader rather than the scholar. They point to a key choice or a difference among the manuscripts.</p>
					<p>It is translated from the original languages (the Hebrew and Aramaic of the Old Testament and the Greek of the New Testament), not adapted from any existing English Bible. Its Old Testament readings are weighed against the Masoretic Hebrew, and its New Testament follows the modern critical text as carried in the major modern translations; where the manuscripts differ, it keeps company with their consensus. Standard Hebrew and Greek reference works are gratefully acknowledged; its English text, notes, and headings are its own.</p>
					<p>Father's Heart Bible™ was produced through a structured, rule-governed translation process built for this work, bringing the consistency and reach of modern language technology to the ancient task of translation. Within that process, AI language tools rendered the text and footnotes directly from the original Hebrew, Aramaic, and Greek, guided by more than 160 translation rules; each book was then carried through successive passes, its most difficult readings cross-checked against the Hebrew and independent references, before being reviewed and finalized. The rules and every interpretive decision are the work of Kevin White of Spirit Media Publishing, who led the process; other readers reviewed it and offered feedback. It is not the work of a translation committee; every rendering is our own, and our own responsibility.</p>
					<p>We hold the church's other faithful translations in genuine honor; Father's Heart Bible™ is offered alongside them, a further window onto the same enduring Word. This is the First Edition (2026), a living text: each edition carries a version number, and corrections are published as the work is refined.</p>
					<p><em>Welcome home. His heart is for you.</em></p>
				</div>

				<p class="mt-10 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
					For copyright, ownership, permissions, and how to quote the Father's Heart Bible™, see <a href="/copyright/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Copyright &amp; Permissions</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
